messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full HTTP request path
- /printshops/history

All HTTP methods acceptable?
- false

Allowed methods (based on the code)
- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: false
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

Explanation
- The controller method is annotated with @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/history", method = RequestMethod.GET) in PrintShopController.java, so the mapped path is exactly "/printshops/history" and the method explicitly accepts GET.
- There is no class-level @RequestMapping prefix on PrintShopController, so the full path is exactly as shown.
- Only RequestMethod.GET is declared; no other HTTP methods (HEAD, POST, OPTIONS, TRACE, PUT, DELETE, PATCH, etc.) are explicitly mapped in the code, so they are marked not acceptable. (Although Spring can implicitly handle HEAD for GET in runtime, the task requested decisions based strictly on the code annotations, not on experiential assumptions, so HEAD is reported as not acceptable.)
- The method is secured with @Secured({"ROLE_MANAGER", "ROLE_EMPLOYEE"}), which limits who may call it but does not change the allowed HTTP methods.
